Common HR Screening Questions
1️⃣ Introduction Questions

Tell me about yourself.

Can you briefly explain your current role?

What technologies are you currently working on?

How many years of experience do you have in DevOps / SRE?

2️⃣ Current Job Questions

What is your current role at Tata Consultancy Services?

What kind of projects are you working on?

Are you working in production support or development?

Do you work on cloud technologies like Amazon Web Services?

3️⃣ Job Change Questions

Why are you looking for a job change?

Why do you want to leave your current company?

What kind of role are you looking for next?

Good answer example:

I am looking for an opportunity where I can work more on DevOps tools, automation, and cloud technologies and grow further in SRE practices.

4️⃣ Salary Questions

What is your current CTC?

What is your expected CTC?

Are you open to negotiation?

5️⃣ Availability Questions

What is your notice period?

Can it be negotiated or bought out?

When can you join if selected?

6️⃣ Work Location Questions

Are you comfortable with relocation?

Are you open to hybrid or office work?

Are you willing to work in on-call or shift support?

7️⃣ Skill Confirmation Questions

Do you have experience with Docker and Kubernetes?

Have you worked on CI/CD pipelines?

Do you have hands-on experience with Linux troubleshooting?

What monitoring tools have you used like Datadog or CloudWatch?

8️⃣ Final HR Questions

Do you have any offers in hand?

Are you interviewing with other companies?

Why should we hire you?

Do you have any questions for us?

Questions You Should Ask HR

At the end of the call, always ask something like:

What will be the next interview rounds?

What technologies does the team mainly work on?

What is the team size and structure?

This shows interest and professionalism.


1️⃣ When HR asks: “What is your current CTC?”

Be honest.

Example:

My current CTC is ₹7 LPA.

Do not over-explain why it is low.

2️⃣ When HR asks: “What is your expected salary?”

Do NOT say 30% hike. That would be too low.

You should answer based on market value, not current salary.

Example answer:

Considering my 8.5 years of experience in Site Reliability Engineering, Linux administration, CI/CD pipelines, Docker, Kubernetes, and cloud platforms, I am looking for an opportunity in the range of ₹16–20 LPA, depending on the role and responsibilities.

This is a normal expectation in Bangalore.

3️⃣ If HR says “This is a big jump from your current salary”

Good response:

Yes, I understand the difference. My current compensation is below the market standard for my experience and skills. I am looking for a role where my experience in production systems, automation, and DevOps tools can be valued closer to market levels.

This sounds professional and confident.

4️⃣ If HR asks “Why are you underpaid?”

Safe answer:

I joined my current role primarily for the learning opportunity and project exposure, especially working on large-scale production systems. Now that I have gained strong experience in SRE practices and DevOps tools, I am looking for compensation aligned with the market.

5️⃣ Important Strategy for You

When asked expected salary, always give a range:

Example:

I am expecting something in the range of ₹16–20 LPA depending on the role.

This allows HR to place you in the middle.

